    "summary": "No — keep ordinals; \"Ultimate\" imports ontological weight the author explicitly disclaims",
    "content": "**No. Keep the ordinal numbering: Zeroth, First, Second.**\n\nThree reasons:\n\n1. **The author explicitly warns against exactly this move.** Footnote 25 says 第一实在 is a 名称 (name), not an ontological claim about what is \"most real.\" Renaming it \"Ultimate Reality\" does precisely what the footnote asks the reader not to do: it imports ontological weight into what is meant as a positional label. \"First\" says \"this is where we start.\" \"Ultimate\" says \"this is what is most real.\" The author means the former.\n\n2. **\"Ultimate Reality\" is already claimed by 第〇实在.** The entire point of the author's framework is that the tradition of metaphysics posits an 终极实在 (ultimate reality) as the ground of everything, and the author argues this is inaccessible --- when we try to articulate it, it immediately becomes Second Reality. If we now label First Reality as \"Ultimate,\" we collapse the distinction between the accessible starting point (phenomena) and the inaccessible metaphysical ground (the Zeroth). This is the very confusion the author's numbering system is designed to prevent.\n\n3. **The ordinal system is the argument.** The numbering 0-1-2 is not arbitrary labeling --- it is a philosophical claim expressed through numbering. The progression says: we posit a ground (0), but what we actually have is phenomena (1), and from phenomena we construct interpretations (2). The ordinals encode the author's epistemological ordering. \"Zeroth/First/Second\" preserves this ordering transparently. \"Ultimate/Secondary\" destroys it by replacing a structural relationship (ordinal sequence) with evaluative adjectives (ultimate = most important, secondary = less important).\n\nFrom a Wittgensteinian perspective specifically: Wittgenstein would say that the ordinal naming is already a perspicuous presentation of the philosophical content. Changing the names to \"Ultimate\" and \"Secondary\" would be adding a philosophical interpretation on top of what is already clear --- making the translation do philosophical work that should be left to the reader."
  }
